Nice combo — both topics are very interview-relevant.
1. TTL Caching in Python
What is TTL caching?
TTL means Time To Live.
A TTL cache stores data for a limited time. After that time expires, the value is considered stale and should be recomputed/refetched.
Example use cases:
Use case
Why TTL helps
API response caching
Avoid repeated external API calls
DB query caching
Reduce database load
Auth/session lookup
Avoid repeated token/user lookups
Config caching
Refresh config after some time
Expensive computation
Avoid recalculating repeatedly
2. Simple TTL cache example in Python
import time
cache = {}
def get_user(user_id):
 ttl = 10 # seconds
 current_time = time.time()
 if user_id in cache:
 value, expiry_time = cache[user_id]
 if current_time < expiry_time:
 print("Returning from cache")
 return value
 print("Cache expired")
 del cache[user_id]
 print("Fetching fresh data")
 user = {
 "id": user_id,
 "name": "Shelendra"
 }

## Page 13

cache[user_id] = (user, current_time + ttl)
 return user
Usage:
print(get_user(1)) # fresh
print(get_user(1)) # cache
Flow:
First call → Fetch fresh data → Store in cache for 10 seconds
Second call → Return cached data
After 10 sec → Cache expires → Fetch fresh data again
3. TTL cache using decorator
This is cleaner if you want to cache function results.
import time
from functools import wraps
def ttl_cache(ttl_seconds):
 cache = {}
 def decorator(func):
 @wraps(func)
 def wrapper(*args, **kwargs):
 key = (args, tuple(sorted(kwargs.items())))
 current_time = time.time()
 if key in cache:
 value, expiry_time = cache[key]
 if current_time < expiry_time:
 print("Cache hit")
 return value
 print("Cache expired")
 del cache[key]
 print("Cache miss")
 result = func(*args, **kwargs)
 cache[key] = (result, current_time + ttl_seconds)
 return result
 return wrapper
 return decorator
Use it like this:

## Page 14

@ttl_cache(ttl_seconds=5)
def fetch_product(product_id):
 print("Fetching product from DB/API")
 return {
 "id": product_id,
 "name": "Laptop"
 }
print(fetch_product(101)) # cache miss
print(fetch_product(101)) # cache hit
4. Using cachetools TTLCache
In real projects, you can use cachetools .
pip install cachetools
bash pip install cachetools
from cachetools import TTLCache
cache = TTLCache(maxsize=100, ttl=60)
def get_user(user_id):
 if user_id in cache:
 return cache[user_id]
 user = {
 "id": user_id,
 "name": "Shelendra"
 }
 cache[user_id] = user
 return user
Meaning:
TTLCache(maxsize=100, ttl=60)
Parameter
Meaning
maxsize=100
Store maximum 100 items
ttl=60
Each item lives for 60 seconds
5. TTL cache side effects in Python
TTL caching is useful, but it has side effects.

## Page 15

1. Stale data
The cache may return old data.
Example:
User changes name in DB
Cache still returns old name for 60 seconds
So TTL should depend on how fresh the data needs to be.
2. Memory usage
If cache size is not limited, memory can grow continuously.
Bad:
cache = {}
Better:
TTLCache(maxsize=1000, ttl=300)
Always use a max size in long-running apps.
3. Harder debugging
You may update DB data but still see old cached response.
Example:
DB says: name = "Rahul"
API returns: name = "Shelendra"
Why?
Because API is returning cached data.
4. Race conditions
In multi-threaded apps, two requests can update or read the cache at the same time.
Example problem:
Request A sees cache expired
Request B also sees cache expired
Both fetch same data from DB/API
For heavy production apps, you may need locks or external cache like Redis.

## Page 16

5. Per-process cache issue
In FastAPI/Flask with multiple workers:
uvicorn app:app --workers 4
Each worker has its own memory.
So this:
cache = {}
is not shared between workers.
Meaning:
Worker 1 cache ≠ Worker 2 cache ≠ Worker 3 cache
For shared caching, use Redis/Memcached.
6. Caching wrong data because of bad keys
This is a common bug.
Bad:
cache["user"] = result
Now all users may get the same cached response.
Better:
cache[f"user:{user_id}"] = result
The cache key must uniquely represent the input.
6. React side effects
Now coming to React.
A side effect means anything that affects something outside the normal rendering process.
Rendering should ideally be pure:
function Component() {
 return <h1>Hello</h1>;
}
But these things are side effects:
Side effect
Example
API call
fetch("/users")

## Page 17

Side effect
Example
Timer
setTimeout , setInterval
Event listener
window.addEventListener
DOM manipulation
document.title = "Home"
Local storage
localStorage.setItem()
WebSocket
Opening socket connection
Subscription
Listening to external store
React handles side effects mainly using useEffect .
7. Basic useEffect
7. basic useeffect
import { useEffect, useState } from "react";
function Users() {
 const [users, setUsers] = useState([]);
 useEffect(() => {
 fetch("https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users")
 .then((res) => res.json())
 .then((data) => setUsers(data));
 }, []);
 return (
 <div>
 {users.map((user) => (
 <p key={user.id}>{user.name}</p>
 ))}
 </div>
 );
}
This effect runs once when the component mounts because dependency array is empty:
[]
8. Dependency array behavior
Runs after every render
s after every render
useEffect(() => {
 console.log("Runs after every render");
});

## Page 18

Runs only once on mount
s only once on mount
useEffect(() => {
 console.log("Runs once");
}, []);
Runs when search changes
s when search changes
useEffect(() => {
 console.log("Search changed");
}, [search]);
9. Cleanup side effects
Some side effects need cleanup.
Example with event listener:
useEffect(() => {
 const handleResize = () => {
 console.log(window.innerWidth);
 };
 window.addEventListener("resize", handleResize);
 return () => {
 window.removeEventListener("resize", handleResize);
 };
}, []);
Without cleanup, you may create memory leaks.
10. Timer side effect
Bad:
useEffect(() => {
 setInterval(() => {
 console.log("Running");
 }, 1000);
}, []);
Problem: interval keeps running even after component unmounts.
Better:
useEffect(() => {
 const intervalId = setInterval(() => {
 console.log("Running");

## Page 19

}, 1000);
 return () => {
 clearInterval(intervalId);
 };
}, []);
11. API call side effects with cleanup
A common issue is setting state after component unmounts.
Better pattern:
useEffect(() => {
 const controller = new AbortController();
 async function fetchUsers() {
 try {
 const response = await fetch("/api/users", {
 signal: controller.signal,
 });
 const data = await response.json();
 setUsers(data);
 } catch (error) {
 if (error.name !== "AbortError") {
 console.error(error);
 }
 }
 }
 fetchUsers();
 return () => {
 controller.abort();
 };
}, []);
This cancels the request if the component unmounts.
12. Common side effect mistakes in React
Mistake 1: Calling API directly in component body
Bad:
function Users() {
 const [users, setUsers] = useState([]);
 fetch("/api/users")
 .then((res) => res.json())
 .then((data) => setUsers(data));

## Page 20

return <div>Users</div>;
}
Why bad?
Every render calls fetch() , and setUsers() causes another render, which calls fetch() again.
This can create an infinite loop.
Correct:
useEffect(() => {
 fetch("/api/users")
 .then((res) => res.json())
 .then((data) => setUsers(data));
}, []);
Mistake 2: Wrong dependencies
Bad:
useEffect(() => {
 fetch(`/api/users/${userId}`)
 .then((res) => res.json())
 .then((data) => setUser(data));
}, []);
If userId changes, this effect will not run again.
Correct:
useEffect(() => {
 fetch(`/api/users/${userId}`)
 .then((res) => res.json())
 .then((data) => setUser(data));
}, [userId]);
Mistake 3: Infinite loop because state is dependency
Bad:
useEffect(() => {
 setCount(count + 1);
}, [count]);
Flow:
count changes → effect runs → setCount → count changes → effect runs again
This can become infinite.

## Page 21

Mistake 4: Forgetting cleanup
Bad:
useEffect(() => {
 window.addEventListener("resize", handleResize);
}, []);
Correct:
useEffect(() => {
 window.addEventListener("resize", handleResize);
 return () => {
 window.removeEventListener("resize", handleResize);
 };
}, []);
13. React side effect interview answer
You can say:
In React, side effects are operations that happen outside the rendering process, such as API calls, timers, subscriptions, manually changing
the DOM, localStorage access, or event listeners. Since React rendering should be pure, side effects are usually handled inside useEffect .
The dependency array controls when the effect runs, and the cleanup function is used to remove subscriptions, timers, event listeners, or
cancel requests. Common mistakes include calling APIs directly inside the component body, missing dependencies, causing infinite re-
renders, and forgetting cleanup.
14. TTL caching + React side effects combined example
Suppose your React app calls a Python backend.
Python backend:
from cachetools import TTLCache
from fastapi import FastAPI
app = FastAPI()
cache = TTLCache(maxsize=100, ttl=60)
@app.get("/products/{product_id}")
def get_product(product_id: int):
 if product_id in cache:
 return {
 "source": "cache",
 "data": cache[product_id]
 }
 product = {
 "id": product_id,
 "name": "Laptop"
 }

## Page 22

cache[product_id] = product
 return {
 "source": "database",
 "data": product
 }
React frontend:
import { useEffect, useState } from "react";
function Product({ productId }) {
 const [product, setProduct] = useState(null);
 useEffect(() => {
 const controller = new AbortController();
 async function fetchProduct() {
 const response = await fetch(`/products/${productId}`, {
 signal: controller.signal,
 });
 const result = await response.json();
 setProduct(result.data);
 }
 fetchProduct();
 return () => {
 controller.abort();
 };
 }, [productId]);
 if (!product) {
 return <p>Loading...</p>;
 }
 return <h1>{product.name}</h1>;
}
Here:
React side effect → API call
Python TTL cache → avoids repeated expensive backend work
15. Final comparison
Topic
Meaning
Main issue
TTL cache in Python
Store data temporarily
Stale data
React side effect
Operation outside render
Infinite render / cleanup bugs
Simple way to remember:

## Page 23

TTL cache controls how long data lives.
React useEffect controls when side effects run.
And the golden rules:
Python TTL cache:
Use correct keys, expiry, max size, and avoid stale data.
React side effects:
Do them in useEffect, manage dependencies, and cleanup properly.
