<h2 id="11-python-testing-for-aws-code">11. Python testing for AWS code</h2>
<h3 id="structure-for-testability">Structure for testability</h3>
<p>Bad:</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">def handler(event, context):
 s3 = boto3.client(&quot;s3&quot;)
 # all logic here
</code></pre>
<p>Better:</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">class InvoiceService:
 def __init__(self, storage, extractor, repository):
 self.storage = storage
 self.extractor = extractor
 self.repository = repository
 def process(self, job):
 document = self.storage.get(job[&quot;bucket&quot;], job[&quot;key&quot;])
 result = self.extractor.extract(document)
 self.repository.save(result)
 return result
</code></pre>
<h3 id="unit-test-with-mock">Unit test with mock</h3>
<pre><code class="language-python">from unittest.mock import Mock
def test_invoice_service_processes_document():
 storage = Mock()
 extractor = Mock()
 repository = Mock()
 storage.get.return_value = b&quot;pdf-data&quot;
 extractor.extract.return_value = {&quot;invoice_no&quot;: &quot;INV-1&quot;}
 service = InvoiceService(storage, extractor, repository)
 result = service.process({&quot;bucket&quot;: &quot;b&quot;, &quot;key&quot;: &quot;k&quot;})
 assert result[&quot;invoice_no&quot;] == &quot;INV-1&quot;
 repository.save.assert_called_once()
</code></pre>
<p>Lead answer:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;I isolate pure business logic from AWS integration code. Then I unit test core logic with mocks and 
integration-test AWS paths separately using dev resources or local emulators where appropriate.&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
