<h2 id="16-lambda-cold-start">16. Lambda cold start</h2>
<p>Cold start happens when Lambda creates a new execution environment.</p>
<p>Cold start phases:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">Container/environment allocation
Runtime initialization
Code/package loading
Global variable initialization
Handler invocation
</code></pre>
<p>Common cold start causes:</p>
<ul>
<li>Large deployment package</li>
<li>Heavy imports like pandas/numpy</li>
<li>VPC configuration</li>
<li>Large layers</li>
<li>Too much initialization code</li>
<li>Low memory allocation</li>
<li>Infrequent traffic</li>
</ul>
<p>Mitigation:</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
 <th>Technique</th>
 <th>Use when</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
 <td>Keep package small</td>
 <td>always</td>
</tr>
<tr>
 <td>Move reusable init outside handler</td>
 <td>always</td>
</tr>
<tr>

## Page 57

<td>Increase memory</td>
 <td>CPU/network often improve with memory</td>
</tr>
<tr>
 <td>Provisioned concurrency</td>
 <td>latency-sensitive workloads</td>
</tr>
<tr>
 <td>Avoid unnecessary VPC</td>
 <td>if no private resource needed</td>
</tr>
<tr>
 <td>Use container image carefully</td>
 <td>for large dependencies, but optimize image</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>Interview answer:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;Cold starts are not always a problem. They matter for synchronous user-facing APIs, but less for async 
batch processing. I optimize based on p95/p99 latency, not guesswork.&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
