<p>Concurrency means number of Lambda invocations running at the same time.</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">concurrency = requests per second * average duration in seconds
</code></pre>
<p>Example:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">100 requests/sec * 0.5 sec = 50 concurrent executions
</code></pre>
<h3 id="reserved-concurrency">Reserved concurrency</h3>
<p>Reserved concurrency guarantees and limits concurrency for a function.</p>
<p>Use cases:</p>
<ul>

## Page 58

<li>Protect database from too many connections</li>
<li>Ensure critical function has capacity</li>
<li>Stop runaway function by setting reserved concurrency to 0</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="provisioned-concurrency">Provisioned concurrency</h3>
<p>Provisioned concurrency keeps environments initialized in advance.</p>
<p>Use cases:</p>
<ul>
<li>Low-latency APIs</li>
<li>Spiky traffic where cold starts matter</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="throttling-scenario">Throttling scenario</h3>
<pre><code class="language-text">SQS backlog grows
Lambda scales up
RDS starts refusing connections
Function errors increase
Messages retry
Backlog grows more
</code></pre>
<p>Lead fix:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">Set reserved concurrency on worker Lambda
Use RDS Proxy or connection pool
Tune SQS batch size and visibility timeout
Make messages idempotent
Add DLQ and alarms
Scale DB if needed
</code></pre>
