<h1 id="part-v---mock-lead-answer-end-to-end-aws-design">PART V - Mock lead answer: end-to-end AWS design</h1>
<p>Question:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Design a scalable document processing system using Python and AWS.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Answer:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>I would split the system into a synchronous ingestion path and an asynchronous processing path. The API 
would authenticate the user, create a job record, and return a pre-signed S3 URL. The frontend uploads the 
document directly to S3 under a raw prefix. An S3 event or EventBridge rule triggers a validator Lambda, which 
sends a normalized job message to SQS. A worker Lambda consumes from SQS, uses an idempotency check based on 
job_id and object version, calls Textract or custom Python processing, stores raw results in S3, and writes 
normalized results to RDS or DynamoDB depending on query needs. For multi-step processing or long-running 
workflows, I would use Step Functions instead of chaining Lambdas manually. For failures, I would use partial 
batch responses, DLQs, retries with backoff, and a job status table. For security, I would use IAM roles with

## Page 98

least privilege, KMS encryption, private DB subnets, pre-signed URLs, and no hardcoded credentials. For 
observability, I would monitor Lambda errors, duration, throttles, SQS backlog and age, DLQ count, DB 
connections, and structured logs with job IDs. For scaling, I would tune Lambda reserved concurrency to protect 
downstream systems, use SQS as a buffer, use RDS Proxy if using RDS, and design S3 prefixes and Glue partitions 
properly for batch analytics.&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
