<h2 id="2-python-memory-references-and-leaks">2. Python memory, references, and leaks</h2>
<p>Python variables are references to objects. This matters in AWS workers because a Lambda execution 
environment can be reused. Global mutable state can survive across invocations.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">cache = {}
def lambda_handler(event, context):
 # This cache may survive across warm invocations.
 # That can be useful for read-only metadata, but dangerous for user-specific data.
 cache[event[&quot;request_id&quot;]] = event
 return {&quot;cache_size&quot;: len(cache)}
</code></pre>
<h3 id="good-global-reuse">Good global reuse</h3>
<pre><code class="language-python">import boto3
s3 = boto3.client(&quot;s3&quot;)
textract = boto3.client(&quot;textract&quot;)
def lambda_handler(event, context):
 # Reusing SDK clients improves performance across warm invocations.
 return process(event, s3=s3, textract=textract)
</code></pre>
<h3 id="bad-global-reuse">Bad global reuse</h3>
<pre><code class="language-python">current_user = None
