<h2 id="4-retry-patterns-in-python">4. Retry patterns in Python</h2>
<p>Retries are powerful but dangerous. Retrying every failure can make outages worse.</p>
<h3 id="retry-only-transient-failures">Retry only transient failures</h3>
<p>Retry:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">- 429 Too Many Requests
- 500/502/503/504
- network timeout
- throttling exception
- temporary service unavailable
</code></pre>
<p>Do not blindly retry:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">- validation error
- AccessDenied
- bad credentials
- malformed input

## Page 103

- duplicate unique key unless idempotency is expected
</code></pre>
<h3 id="retry-decorator-1">Retry decorator</h3>
<pre><code class="language-python">import time
import random
from functools import wraps
class TransientError(Exception):
 pass
def retry(max_attempts=3, base_delay=0.5, max_delay=5):
 def decorator(fn):
 @wraps(fn)
 def wrapper(*args, **kwargs):
 attempt = 0
 while True:
 try:
 return fn(*args, **kwargs)
 except TransientError:
 attempt += 1
 if attempt &gt;= max_attempts:
 raise
 sleep = min(max_delay, base_delay * (2 ** (attempt - 1)))
 sleep = sleep + random.uniform(0, 0.2) # jitter
 time.sleep(sleep)
 return wrapper
 return decorator
</code></pre>
<h3 id="why-jitter-matters">Why jitter matters</h3>
<p>Without jitter, many failed workers retry at the same time and create a retry storm. Jitter spreads retries.
</p>
<p>Lead answer:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;I use exponential backoff with jitter for transient failures, but I combine it with idempotency and a 
maximum retry count. For async queues, I prefer queue-level retry and DLQ rather than infinite in-code 
retries.&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2 id="5-idempotency-in-python-workers">5. Idempotency in Python workers</h2>
<p>Idempotency means processing the same event multiple times does not create wrong duplicate side effects.</p>
<h3 id="why-idempotency-is-mandatory-in-aws">Why idempotency is mandatory in AWS</h3>
<p>Many AWS event sources are at-least-once. SQS, SNS, EventBridge, Lambda async retries, and network failures 
can cause duplicate processing.</p>
<h3 id="idempotent-sqs-processing-pattern">Idempotent SQS processing pattern</h3>
<pre><code class="language-python">import hashlib
