<h3 id="scaling-scenario-sudden-spike">Scaling scenario: sudden spike</h3>
<p>Question:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;Your Lambda gets a sudden traffic spike and users see timeouts. What do you check?&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Answer structure:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">1. CloudWatch metrics: invocations, duration, errors, throttles, concurrent 
executions.
2. API Gateway metrics: 4XX, 5XX, integration latency.
3. Lambda timeout and memory.
4. Downstream dependencies: RDS connections, external API rate limits, S3/SQS errors.
5. Concurrency limits: reserved/account concurrency.
6. Recent deployment/config changes.
7. Mitigation: increase memory/concurrency, reduce timeout bottleneck, queue async work, rollback bad deploy, 
protect downstream.
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h2 id="13-lambda-timeout-memory-and-cpu">13. Lambda timeout, memory, and CPU</h2>
<p>Lambda CPU scales with memory. Increasing memory can reduce duration and sometimes reduce cost if execution 
becomes much faster.</p>
<h3 id="timeout-design">Timeout design</h3>
<p>Bad:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">Set timeout to 15 minutes for everything.
</code></pre>
<p>Better:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">API Lambda: short timeout, e.g. 5-30 seconds.
Worker Lambda: based on batch size and downstream latency.
Glue/ECS/Batch: for long heavy jobs.
</code></pre>
<h3 id="what-happens-when-timeout-occurs">What happens when timeout occurs?</h3>
<p>The process is stopped. Any partial side effects before timeout may already exist.</p>
<p>Therefore:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">- Write status transitions carefully.
- Use idempotency.
- Use checkpoints for long work.
- Do not process too many records in one invocation.
</code></pre>
