<h2 id="19-s3-upload-patterns">19. S3 upload patterns</h2>
<h3 id="direct-upload-through-backend">Direct upload through backend</h3>
<pre><code class="language-text">React -&gt; Flask/FastAPI -&gt; S3
</code></pre>
<p>Pros:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">- backend controls validation
- easy auth enforcement
</code></pre>
<p>Cons:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">- backend handles file bandwidth
- API can timeout for large files
</code></pre>
<h3 id="presigned-url-upload">Presigned URL upload</h3>
<pre><code class="language-text">React -&gt; backend asks for signed URL -&gt; React uploads directly to S3
</code></pre>
<p>Pros:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">- backend does not carry file bytes
- scalable for large files
</code></pre>
<p>Cons:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">- must validate file type/size/key rules
- CORS needed on S3 bucket
- object key security matters
</code></pre>
<p>Example:</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">import boto3
s3 = boto3.client(&quot;s3&quot;)
def create_upload_url(bucket, key, content_type):
 return s3.generate_presigned_url(
 ClientMethod=&quot;put_object&quot;,
 Params={
 &quot;Bucket&quot;: bucket,
 &quot;Key&quot;: key,
 &quot;ContentType&quot;: content_type,
 },
 ExpiresIn=900,

## Page 117

)
</code></pre>
<p>Lead answer:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;For large user uploads, I prefer presigned URLs so the browser uploads directly to S3. The backend 
creates a job record and controls the allowed key, content type, expiration, and user ownership.&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
