<h1 id="part-v2-e---queues-events-and-async-architecture">PART V2-E - Queues, Events, and Async 
Architecture</h1>
<h2 id="23-why-queues-exist">23. Why queues exist</h2>
<p>Queues solve mismatch between producer speed and consumer speed.</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">Without queue:
 user/API -&gt; slow worker -&gt; timeout/failure
With queue:
 user/API -&gt; enqueue job -&gt; fast response
 worker processes later with retries
</code></pre>
<p>Queues provide:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">- buffering
- retry control
- decoupling
- backpressure
- async processing
- failure isolation
</code></pre>
<p>But queues introduce:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">- eventual consistency
- duplicate processing
- ordering issues
- DLQ replay complexity
- harder debugging
</code></pre>
<p>Lead answer:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;Queues improve resilience, but they shift complexity into idempotency, monitoring, ordering, and

## Page 119

replay. I design those explicitly.&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
