<h2 id="34-glue-bookmarks">34. Glue bookmarks</h2>
<p>Job bookmarks track processed data so repeated runs can process only new data.</p>
<p>Use bookmarks when:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">- periodic incremental ETL
- S3/JDBC sources
- avoid reprocessing old files
</code></pre>
<p>Be careful:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">- bookmarks are not magic business idempotency
- changing source path/schema can affect behavior
- backfills may need bookmark reset or separate job
</code></pre>
<p>Lead answer:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;Glue bookmarks help avoid reprocessing old source data, but I still design output idempotency. For 
backfills, I use a controlled separate run or reset bookmarks carefully.&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2 id="35-glue-job-failing-at-scale">35. Glue job failing at scale</h2>
<p>Question:</p>

## Page 125

<blockquote>
<p>&quot;A Glue job works for 10 GB but fails for 200 GB. What do you check?&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Strong answer:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">1. Check CloudWatch/Spark UI logs for OOM, executor lost, shuffle errors.
2. Check input format: CSV vs Parquet, compression, file size distribution.
3. Check small files problem or few huge files.
4. Check transformations: joins, groupBy, distinct, repartition, collect.
5. Check data skew: one key has most records.
6. Check worker type/count and Glue version.
7. Check partition pruning and pushdown predicates.
8. Check output partitioning and S3 write behavior.
9. Tune code: select fewer columns, filter early, avoid collect, broadcast small dimension table, repartition 
strategically.
10. Rerun on sample and then scale gradually.
</code></pre>
<h3 id="bad-spark-code">Bad Spark code</h3>
<pre><code class="language-python">rows = df.collect() # brings all data to driver, can crash
for row in rows:
 print(row)
</code></pre>
<h3 id="better">Better</h3>
<pre><code class="language-python">filtered = df.select(&quot;id&quot;, &quot;status&quot;, 
&quot;created_at&quot;).filter(&quot;status = 'ACTIVE'&quot;)
filtered.write.mode(&quot;overwrite&quot;).parquet(&quot;s3://bucket/output/&quot;)
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h2 id="36-small-files-problem">36. Small files problem</h2>
<p>Many small files in S3 can make Glue/Spark slow because each file creates overhead.</p>
<p>Symptoms:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">- job spends long time listing/reading
- huge number of tasks
- slow Athena queries
- high S3 request cost
</code></pre>
<p>Fixes:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">- compact files into larger Parquet files
- partition sensibly
- avoid writing one tiny output file per event
- use batch/stream compaction job
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h2 id="37-data-lake-layout">37. Data lake layout</h2>
<p>Good S3 layout:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">s3://data-lake/raw/source=crm/year=2026/month=06/day=18/
s3://data-lake/curated/table=invoices/year=2026/month=06/day=18/
s3://data-lake/analytics/invoice_summary/year=2026/month=06/
</code></pre>
<p>Why partition by date/source?</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">- faster queries through partition pruning
- easier lifecycle management
- easier backfills
- easier debugging
</code></pre>
