<h2 id="39-postgresql-indexes-for-interviews">39. PostgreSQL indexes for interviews</h2>
<h3 id="b-tree-index">B-tree index</h3>
<p>Default, good for equality and range.</p>
<pre><code class="language-sql">CREATE INDEX idx_users_email ON users(email);
CREATE INDEX idx_orders_created_at ON orders(created_at);
</code></pre>
<h3 id="composite-index">Composite index</h3>
<pre><code class="language-sql">CREATE INDEX idx_orders_user_status_created
ON orders(user_id, status, created_at DESC);
</code></pre>
<p>Index order matters. This index helps:</p>
<pre><code class="language-sql">WHERE user_id = 10 AND status = 'PAID'
ORDER BY created_at DESC
</code></pre>
<h3 id="explain-analyze">Explain analyze</h3>
<pre><code class="language-sql">EXPLAIN ANALYZE
SELECT * FROM orders
WHERE user_id = 10
ORDER BY created_at DESC
LIMIT 20;
</code></pre>
<p>Lead answer:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;I do not add indexes blindly. I look at query patterns and execution plans. Indexes speed reads but 
slow writes and consume storage.&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
