<h1 id="part-v2-p---cost-optimization">PART V2-P - Cost Optimization</h1>
<h2 id="69-lambda-cost-levers">69. Lambda cost levers</h2>
<pre><code class="language-text">cost roughly depends on requests + duration * memory
</code></pre>
<p>Optimization:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">- reduce duration
- tune memory for better CPU
- avoid unnecessary invocations
- batch SQS records
- avoid recursive triggers
- use provisioned concurrency only where needed
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h2 id="70-glue-cost-levers">70. Glue cost levers</h2>
<pre><code class="language-text">- DPU hours

## Page 145

- worker type/count
- job duration
- inefficient transformations
- small files
- repeated full reprocessing
</code></pre>
<p>Optimization:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">- bookmarks/incremental loads
- partition pruning
- Parquet instead of CSV
- filter early
- right-size worker type
- compact small files
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h2 id="71-nat-gateway-hidden-cost">71. NAT Gateway hidden cost</h2>
<p>NAT Gateway can become expensive when private subnets send large traffic through it.</p>
<p>Mitigation:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">- use S3 Gateway Endpoint
- use DynamoDB Gateway Endpoint
- use Interface VPC Endpoints for supported services
- avoid routing heavy AWS-service traffic through NAT
</code></pre>
<p>Lead answer:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;If I see unexpected network cost, I check NAT Gateway data processing, cross-AZ traffic, cross-region 
traffic, and whether VPC endpoints should be used.&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
