</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2 id="73-why-should-we-consider-you-for-a-lead-role-with-4-years-experience">73. Why should we consider you 
for a lead role with 4 years experience?</h2>
<p>Strong answer:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;I understand the concern. My total experience is around 4 years, but I have been working on production 
systems where I had to own features, debug issues, coordinate with teams, and understand system flow beyond 
just writing code. For this role, I would bring strong Python development, practical AWS exposure, and a very 
ownership-driven approach. I may have areas to deepen, especially across some AWS infrastructure services, but 
I learn fast and I reason from fundamentals: trigger, compute, storage, network, security, observability, 
scaling, and failure modes. That mindset is what I would bring to the lead position.&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2 id="74-how-do-you-debug-a-production-issue">74. How do you debug a production issue?</h2>
<p>Strong answer:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;I first confirm the user impact and whether the issue is ongoing. Then I check dashboards and metrics 
to identify whether it is latency, errors, throttling, backlog, or dependency failure. I correlate the time 
window with recent deployments or config changes. Then I go into logs using correlation IDs or job IDs. If the

## Page 146

system is unstable, I mitigate first through rollback, disabling a feature, increasing capacity, or pausing 
consumers. After stability, I do RCA and add preventive actions like tests, alarms, retries, or runbook 
updates.&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2 id="75-how-would-you-design-a-reliable-async-pipeline">75. How would you design a reliable async pipeline?
</h2>
<p>Strong answer:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;I would decouple ingestion from processing using a durable queue. The API validates input, stores 
minimal state, and enqueues a job. Workers process messages idempotently, update status, and send failures to 
DLQ after controlled retries. I would monitor queue age, error rate, processing duration, and DLQ depth. If 
ordering is required, I would evaluate FIFO queue or per-entity ordering. If not, I would choose Standard SQS 
for throughput.&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2 id="76-when-would-you-not-use-lambda">76. When would you not use Lambda?</h2>
<p>Strong answer:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;I would avoid Lambda for very long-running jobs, heavy CPU-bound processing, workloads needing stable 
long-lived connections, large dependencies with cold start sensitivity, or processes requiring local disk 
beyond configured limits. For those, ECS Fargate, Batch, Glue, or EC2 may be better depending on the 
workload.&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2 id="77-how-do-you-prevent-duplicate-processing">77. How do you prevent duplicate processing?</h2>
<p>Strong answer:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;I assume duplicate events can happen. I create an idempotency key from stable business identifiers 
like event_id, job_id, object key, and version. Before side effects, I check or insert this key atomically in a 
database. For SQS batch processing, I use partial batch responses where appropriate, but still keep idempotency 
because duplicates can occur.&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2 id="78-how-do-you-decide-between-rds-and-dynamodb">78. How do you decide between RDS and DynamoDB?</h2>
<p>Strong answer:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;If data is relational, needs joins, strong ad-hoc querying, transactions, and constraints, I prefer 
RDS/PostgreSQL. If access patterns are predictable, high-scale key-value/document access is needed, and the 
schema can be designed around partition/sort keys, DynamoDB is strong. I would not choose DynamoDB unless 
access patterns are clear.&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2 id="79-how-would-you-improve-a-slow-glue-job">79. How would you improve a slow Glue job?</h2>
<p>Strong answer:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;I would start from logs and Spark stages. I would check whether the job is reading too many small 
files, doing wide shuffles, joining skewed data, using collect/toPandas, missing partition pruning, or using 
insufficient workers. Then I would filter early, select only required columns, convert to Parquet, partition 
correctly, compact files, tune worker type/count, and handle skew or broadcast small dimensions.&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
