<h1 id="part-v2-s---practice-scenarios">PART V2-S - Practice Scenarios</h1>
<h2 id="82-scenario-1-million-sqs-messages-backlog">82. Scenario: 1 million SQS messages backlog</h2>
<p>Question:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;SQS has 1 million messages and Lambda is draining slowly. What do you do?&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Answer:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">1. Check ApproximateAgeOfOldestMessage and visible messages.
2. Check Lambda errors, duration, throttles, concurrency.
3. Check batch size and batch window.
4. Check reserved concurrency and event source maximum concurrency.
5. Check downstream bottleneck: DB/API/S3/Textract throttling.
6. Increase concurrency only if downstream can handle it.
7. Increase memory if CPU-bound or duration high.
8. Use partial batch response to avoid retrying successes.
9. Scale out consumers or use ECS if processing is long/heavy.
10. Monitor DLQ and process backlog safely.
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h2 id="83-scenario-user-upload-api-timing-out">83. Scenario: User upload API timing out</h2>
<p>Solution:</p>

## Page 149

<pre><code class="language-text">Move file upload out of API path:
1. API creates job record.
2. API returns presigned S3 URL.
3. Browser uploads directly to S3.
4. S3/SQS triggers async processing.
5. API returns job status.
</code></pre>
<p>Why:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">- avoids API Gateway/Lambda payload/time limits
- improves scalability
- separates upload from processing
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h2 id="84-scenario-s3-triggered-lambda-invokes-repeatedly">84. Scenario: S3-triggered Lambda invokes 
repeatedly</h2>
<p>Answer:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">Likely recursive trigger. Lambda writes output to same prefix/bucket watched 
by trigger. Fix with prefix/suffix filters, separate raw/processed prefixes, separate output bucket, and 
defensive key checks in code. Also check cost impact and throttle/disable trigger while mitigating.&quot;
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h2 id="85-scenario-accessdenied-after-enabling-sse-kms-on-s3-bucket">85. Scenario: AccessDenied after enabling 
SSE-KMS on S3 bucket</h2>
<p>Answer:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">The role may have s3:GetObject but not kms:Decrypt, or the KMS key policy does 
not allow that principal. I would check Lambda execution role, bucket policy, KMS key policy, and CloudTrail 
event details.&quot;
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h2 id="86-scenario-glue-crawler-changed-schema-and-athena-queries-broke">86. Scenario: Glue crawler changed 
schema and Athena queries broke</h2>
<p>Answer:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">I would check crawler configuration, schema evolution settings, table versions 
in Data Catalog, recent raw data files, and whether malformed/new columns caused type inference changes. For 
production, I prefer controlled schema contracts for curated tables rather than blindly allowing crawler 
changes to break consumers.&quot;
</code></pre>
