<h1 id="part-b---aws-foundations">PART B - AWS Foundations</h1>
<h2 id="12-aws-mental-model">12. AWS mental model</h2>
<p>Think of AWS as layers:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">Identity IAM, roles, policies, STS
Network VPC, subnets, route tables, SG, NACL, NAT, IGW
Compute Lambda, EC2, ECS, EKS, Glue jobs
Storage S3, EBS, EFS
Database RDS/Aurora, DynamoDB, ElastiCache

## Page 195

Messaging SQS, SNS, EventBridge, Kafka/MSK
Integration API Gateway, Step Functions, EventBridge Pipes
Security KMS, Secrets Manager, WAF, CloudTrail
Observability CloudWatch, X-Ray, logs, metrics, alarms
Deployment CodePipeline, CodeBuild, SAM/CDK/Terraform
</code></pre>
<p>Lead-level habit:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>For every AWS service, know the trigger, scaling model, retry model, security model, cost driver, and 
failure mode.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2 id="13-iam-from-scratch">13. IAM from scratch</h2>
<p>IAM controls who can do what on which AWS resource.</p>
<h3 id="iam-terms">IAM terms</h3>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
 <th>Term</th>
 <th>Meaning</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
 <td>User</td>
 <td>Long-term identity, usually human or legacy app</td>
</tr>
<tr>
 <td>Group</td>
 <td>Collection of users</td>
</tr>
<tr>
 <td>Role</td>
 <td>Assumable identity with temporary credentials</td>
</tr>
<tr>
 <td>Policy</td>
 <td>JSON permission document</td>
</tr>
<tr>
 <td>Principal</td>
 <td>Who is allowed/denied</td>
</tr>
<tr>
 <td>Action</td>
 <td>What API operation is allowed</td>
</tr>
<tr>
 <td>Resource</td>
 <td>Which AWS resource</td>
</tr>
<tr>
 <td>Condition</td>
 <td>When/how permission applies</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h3 id="policy-example">Policy example</h3>
<pre><code class="language-json">{

## Page 196

&quot;Version&quot;: &quot;2012-10-17&quot;,
 &quot;Statement&quot;: [
 {
 &quot;Effect&quot;: &quot;Allow&quot;,
 &quot;Action&quot;: [&quot;s3:GetObject&quot;],
 &quot;Resource&quot;: &quot;arn:aws:s3:::my-bucket/raw/*&quot;
 }
 ]
}
</code></pre>
<h3 id="lambda-execution-role">Lambda execution role</h3>
<p>A Lambda function does not use your personal credentials. It assumes an IAM role.</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">Lambda function
 -&gt; assumes execution role
 -&gt; role policy allows s3:GetObject, sqs:SendMessage, logs:CreateLogStream, etc.
</code></pre>
<h3 id="lead-level-iam-answer">Lead-level IAM answer</h3>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;For production workloads I avoid long-lived access keys. I use IAM roles, least privilege, resource-
specific ARNs, separate dev/test/prod roles, KMS permissions where needed, and CloudTrail/IAM Access Analyzer 
to review access.&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
<h3 id="common-iam-issues">Common IAM issues</h3>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
 <th>Error</th>
 <th>Likely cause</th>
 <th>Fix</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
 <td>AccessDenied</td>
 <td>Missing identity policy or resource policy</td>
 <td>Check caller identity, action, resource ARN</td>
</tr>
<tr>
 <td>Lambda cannot write logs</td>
 <td>Missing CloudWatch Logs permissions</td>
 <td>Add AWSLambdaBasicExecutionRole or equivalent</td>
</tr>
<tr>
 <td>S3 trigger cannot invoke Lambda</td>
 <td>Missing Lambda resource-based permission</td>
 <td>Add permission for S3 principal</td>
</tr>
<tr>
 <td>KMS decrypt denied</td>
 <td>Role lacks <code>kms:Decrypt</code></td>
 <td>Add KMS key policy and IAM permission</td>
</tr>
<tr>
 <td>Cross-account access fails</td>
 <td>Trust/resource policy missing</td>
 <td>Configure trust relationship and resource policy</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>

