<h2 id="14-vpc-basics-for-pythonaws-engineers">14. VPC basics for Python/AWS engineers</h2>
<p>A VPC is your private network in AWS.</p>
<h3 id="core-components">Core components</h3>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
 <th>Component</th>
 <th>Role</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
 <td>VPC</td>
 <td>isolated network boundary</td>
</tr>
<tr>
 <td>Subnet</td>
 <td>slice of VPC CIDR in one AZ</td>
</tr>
<tr>
 <td>Public subnet</td>
 <td>route to Internet Gateway</td>
</tr>
<tr>
 <td>Private subnet</td>
 <td>no direct internet route</td>
</tr>
<tr>
 <td>Internet Gateway</td>
 <td>internet access for public resources</td>
</tr>
<tr>
 <td>NAT Gateway</td>
 <td>outbound internet from private subnet</td>
</tr>
<tr>
 <td>Route table</td>
 <td>decides where traffic goes</td>
</tr>
<tr>
 <td>Security group</td>
 <td>stateful firewall at ENI/resource level</td>
</tr>
<tr>
 <td>NACL</td>
 <td>stateless subnet-level firewall</td>
</tr>
<tr>
 <td>VPC endpoint</td>
 <td>private path to AWS services without internet</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h3 id="public-vs-private-subnet">Public vs private subnet</h3>
<pre><code class="language-text">Public subnet:
 route 0.0.0.0/0 -&gt; Internet Gateway
 resource needs public IP/EIP for inbound internet

## Page 198

Private subnet:
 no direct route to Internet Gateway
 outbound route may go through NAT Gateway
</code></pre>
<h3 id="lambda-in-vpc">Lambda in VPC</h3>
<p>Use VPC Lambda when it must access private RDS, ElastiCache, internal services, or private subnets.</p>
<p>Common issue:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Lambda in private subnet cannot access internet.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Why?</p>
<ul>
<li>It has no public IP.</li>
<li>It needs route to NAT Gateway for outbound internet.</li>
<li>Or use VPC endpoints for AWS services like S3/SQS/Secrets Manager.</li>
</ul>
<p>Lead answer:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;Before putting Lambda into a VPC, I ask what private resource it needs. If it only needs 
S3/SQS/DynamoDB, VPC may not be necessary. If it needs RDS or Redis in private subnet, I configure private 
subnets, security groups, route tables, NAT or VPC endpoints, and observe ENI/cold-start implications.&quot;
</p>
</blockquote>
