<p>Lambda is event-driven compute. You provide code; AWS manages servers. It scales by creating execution 
environments for concurrent invocations.</p>
<h3 id="lambda-request-lifecycle">Lambda request lifecycle</h3>
<pre><code class="language-text">Event arrives
 -&gt; Lambda service receives invocation
 -&gt; finds existing warm execution environment or creates new one
 -&gt; initializes runtime and global code if cold start
 -&gt; calls handler(event, context)
 -&gt; handler returns or raises or times out
 -&gt; logs and metrics go to CloudWatch
</code></pre>
<h3 id="python-handler">Python handler</h3>
<pre><code class="language-python">import json
import boto3
s3 = boto3.client(&quot;s3&quot;) # initialized outside handler for reuse
def lambda_handler(event, context):
 print(json.dumps(event))
 return {&quot;statusCode&quot;: 200, &quot;body&quot;: &quot;ok&quot;}
</code></pre>
<h3 id="why-initialize-clients-outside-handler">Why initialize clients outside handler?</h3>
<p>Because warm execution environments can reuse global objects. This reduces repeated setup overhead.</p>
