<h2 id="40-scenario-2-lambda-overwhelms-rds">40. Scenario 2: Lambda overwhelms RDS</h2>
<h3 id="problem">Problem</h3>
<pre><code class="language-text">Traffic spike -&gt; Lambda concurrency jumps -&gt; each invocation opens DB 
connection -&gt; RDS max connections exhausted
</code></pre>
<h3 id="fix-options">Fix options</h3>
<ol>
<li>RDS Proxy.</li>
<li>Lambda reserved concurrency.</li>
<li>Queue writes through SQS.</li>
<li>Use connection reuse.</li>
<li>Use batch writes where possible.</li>
<li>Scale DB or move high-cardinality state to DynamoDB.</li>
</ol>
<p>Interview answer:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;I would first stabilize by limiting Lambda concurrency or temporarily disabling the trigger. Then I 
would inspect DB connections, Lambda duration, error rate, and SQS backlog. Permanent fix may include RDS 
Proxy, reserved concurrency, queue buffering, and query/index optimization.&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2 id="41-scenario-3-glue-job-fails-with-oom">41. Scenario 3: Glue job fails with OOM</h2>
<h3 id="possible-causes">Possible causes</h3>
<ul>
<li>Too many small files.</li>
<li>Bad partitioning.</li>
<li>Driver listing huge number of S3 objects.</li>
<li>Data skew.</li>
<li>Large shuffle/join.</li>
<li>Worker type too small.</li>
<li>Unbounded collect/toPandas.</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="fix-approach">Fix approach</h3>
<pre><code class="language-text">Check logs and Spark UI
Check stage where failure happens
Inspect input file sizes/counts
Avoid collect/toPandas on large data
Repartition carefully
Use partition pruning
Compact small files
Increase worker type/count only after data-layout checks
</code></pre>
<p>Bad:</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">df.toPandas() # can crash driver on large data
</code></pre>
<p>Better:</p>
<pre><code class="language-
python">df.write.mode(&quot;overwrite&quot;).parquet(&quot;s3://bucket/output/&quot;)
</code></pre>
