<h1 id="part-p---interview-qampa">PART P - Interview Q&amp;A</h1>
<h2 id="58-lambda-questions">58. Lambda questions</h2>
<h3 id="q1-what-happens-when-lambda-receives-many-requests-at-once">Q1. What happens when Lambda receives many 
requests at once?</h3>
<p>Strong answer:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Lambda scales by creating more execution environments up to concurrency limits and scaling behavior limits. 
If concurrency is exhausted, invocations may throttle depending on invocation type. For downstream systems like 
RDS, uncontrolled concurrency can cause overload, so I use reserved concurrency, SQS buffering, and connection 
pooling/proxy where needed.</p>
</blockquote>
<h3 id="q2-how-do-you-handle-duplicate-sqs-messages">Q2. How do you handle duplicate SQS messages?</h3>
<blockquote>
<p>I assume at-least-once delivery and make the consumer idempotent. I use a job ID or message ID as 
idempotency key, store processing state, and make writes conditional where possible. I also configure DLQ and 
partial batch responses.</p>
</blockquote>

## Page 257

<h3 id="q3-lambda-timeout-vs-sqs-visibility-timeout">Q3. Lambda timeout vs SQS visibility timeout?</h3>
<blockquote>
<p>Lambda timeout is how long the function can run. SQS visibility timeout is how long a received message stays 
hidden. For SQS-triggered Lambda, visibility timeout should be long enough for processing and retries; 
otherwise the message may reappear while still being processed.</p>
</blockquote>
<h3 id="q4-why-use-sqs-between-s3-and-lambda">Q4. Why use SQS between S3 and Lambda?</h3>
<blockquote>
<p>Direct S3-to-Lambda is simple, but SQS adds buffering, retry control, DLQ, backpressure, and replayability. 
It is better when processing can fail, downstream capacity is limited, or upload spikes are expected.</p>
</blockquote>
<h3 id="q5-how-do-you-prevent-lambda-recursive-loops">Q5. How do you prevent Lambda recursive loops?</h3>
<blockquote>
<p>I separate input and output prefixes/buckets, configure event filters carefully, and avoid writing output to 
the same prefix that triggers the function. I also monitor recursive invocation metrics and cost anomalies.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2 id="59-s3-questions">59. S3 questions</h2>
<h3 id="q1-is-s3-a-filesystem">Q1. Is S3 a filesystem?</h3>
<blockquote>
<p>No. S3 is object storage. Keys may look like paths, but there are no real directories. Prefixes are logical. 
This affects renames, listings, and application design.</p>
</blockquote>
<h3 id="q2-how-do-you-upload-large-files">Q2. How do you upload large files?</h3>
<blockquote>
<p>Use multipart upload or SDK helpers like <code>upload_file</code>, and for browser uploads use pre-signed 
URLs so the file goes directly to S3 instead of through the API server.</p>
</blockquote>
<h3 id="q3-how-do-lifecycle-policies-help">Q3. How do lifecycle policies help?</h3>
<blockquote>
<p>Lifecycle policies reduce cost by transitioning objects to cheaper storage classes or deleting old/temporary 
data. They can also abort incomplete multipart uploads.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2 id="60-glue-questions">60. Glue questions</h2>
<h3 id="q1-why-is-my-glue-job-slow">Q1. Why is my Glue job slow?</h3>
<blockquote>
<p>I would check input file size/count, partitioning, schema inference, shuffle stages, skew, worker 
type/count, and whether the job is reading unnecessary partitions. Many Glue performance issues come from data 
layout, not just code.</p>
</blockquote>
<h3 id="q2-dynamicframe-vs-dataframe">Q2. DynamicFrame vs DataFrame?</h3>
<blockquote>
<p>DynamicFrame is Glue's abstraction useful for semi-structured data and Glue transformations. Spark DataFrame 
is Spark-native and often better for complex Spark operations and performance tuning. I convert depending on 
the operation.</p>
</blockquote>
<h3 id="q3-what-are-job-bookmarks">Q3. What are job bookmarks?</h3>
<blockquote>
<p>Job bookmarks track previously processed data so incremental jobs can avoid reprocessing old inputs, but 
they require correct bookmark enablement and transformation context.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2 id="61-vpciam-questions">61. VPC/IAM questions</h2>
<h3 id="q1-lambda-in-private-subnet-cannot-access-internet-why">Q1. Lambda in private subnet cannot access 
internet. Why?</h3>
<blockquote>
<p>Lambda ENIs in private subnets do not get public IPs. For outbound internet, route private subnet traffic 
through NAT Gateway, or use VPC endpoints for AWS services.</p>

## Page 258

</blockquote>
<h3 id="q2-security-group-vs-nacl">Q2. Security group vs NACL?</h3>
<blockquote>
<p>Security groups are stateful and attached to resources/ENIs. NACLs are stateless and apply at subnet level. 
Most application-level access control is done with security groups.</p>
</blockquote>
<h3 id="q3-how-do-you-debug-accessdenied">Q3. How do you debug AccessDenied?</h3>
<blockquote>
<p>I identify the principal using STS/CloudTrail, check the exact denied action and resource ARN, then inspect 
identity policy, resource policy, permission boundary, SCP, session policy, and KMS key policy if encryption is 
involved.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2 id="62-python-questions">62. Python questions</h2>
<h3 id="q1-threading-vs-multiprocessing">Q1. Threading vs multiprocessing?</h3>
<blockquote>
<p>Threads are useful for I/O-bound tasks, but CPU-bound Python bytecode is limited by the GIL in CPython. 
Multiprocessing uses separate processes and can utilize multiple CPUs, but data must be serialized and process 
startup has overhead.</p>
</blockquote>
<h3 id="q2-generator-vs-list">Q2. Generator vs list?</h3>
<blockquote>
<p>A list stores all values in memory. A generator yields values lazily. For large S3 listings, logs, CSVs, or 
ETL streams, generators reduce memory pressure.</p>
</blockquote>
<h3 id="q3-how-do-you-structure-production-python-code">Q3. How do you structure production Python code?</h3>
<blockquote>
<p>I separate API/handler layer, service layer, repository/integration layer, and configuration. I use type 
hints, logging, tests, dependency injection, and avoid putting all business logic inside Lambda handlers or 
route functions.</p>
</blockquote>
