<h3 id="visibility-timeout-rule">Visibility timeout rule</h3>
<pre><code class="language-text">visibility timeout should be greater than Lambda timeout + retry/network 
buffer
</code></pre>
<p>If Lambda timeout is 60 seconds, visibility timeout should usually be comfortably higher, such as 2-3 
minutes depending on processing.</p>
<h3 id="partial-batch-response">Partial batch response</h3>
<p>Without partial batch response, if one message fails in a batch of 10, the whole batch may be retried. With 
partial batch response, successful messages do not need to be retried.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">def lambda_handler(event, context):
 failed = []
 for record in event[&quot;Records&quot;]:
 try:
 process_record(record)
 except Exception:
 failed.append({&quot;itemIdentifier&quot;: record[&quot;messageId&quot;]})
 return {&quot;batchItemFailures&quot;: failed}
</code></pre>
<p>Lead answer:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;For SQS batch processing, I prefer partial batch responses when records are independent. This avoids 
reprocessing successful records and improves throughput, but the handler must be idempotent because duplicates 
are still possible.&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
