<h2 id="16-lambda-rds-issue-connection-storms">16. Lambda + RDS issue: connection storms</h2>
<p>Problem:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">Lambda scales rapidly.
Each invocation opens a DB connection.
RDS max connections are exhausted.
Users see timeouts/errors.
</code></pre>
<p>Bad code:</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">def lambda_handler(event, context):
 conn = psycopg.connect(DB_URL)
 # query
 conn.close()
</code></pre>
<p>Possible fixes:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">- Use RDS Proxy.
- Reuse connection carefully across warm invocations.
- Limit Lambda reserved concurrency.
- Use connection pooling in container-based services.
- Move heavy async DB writes behind SQS.
- Optimize queries and indexes.
- Use DynamoDB if access pattern is key-value and high-scale.
</code></pre>
<p>Lead answer:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;Serverless compute can scale faster than relational databases. I protect RDS using RDS Proxy, reserved 
concurrency, short transactions, efficient indexes, and sometimes async buffering through SQS.&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
