<h2 id="20-s3-event-notification-pitfalls">20. S3 event notification pitfalls</h2>
<p>Common issue:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">S3 trigger invokes Lambda repeatedly in a loop.
</code></pre>
<p>Cause:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">Lambda reads from raw/ and writes output back into a prefix that also triggers 
the same Lambda.
</code></pre>
<p>Fix:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">- Use separate prefixes: raw/ input and processed/ output.
- Add suffix/prefix filters.
- Write output to a different bucket.
- Make the Lambda ignore keys that are not input.
</code></pre>
<p>Safe pattern:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">raw/ triggers processing
processed/ does not trigger same Lambda
failed/ does not trigger same Lambda
</code></pre>
<h3 id="s3-event-not-triggering-lambda-checklist">S3 event not triggering Lambda checklist</h3>
<pre><code class="language-text">1. Is event notification configured on correct bucket?
2. Prefix/suffix filter correct?
3. Lambda resource policy allows S3 invocation?
4. Object created by multipart complete event?
5. Is Lambda in same/allowed region?
6. Are CloudWatch logs created?
7. Are events sent to EventBridge instead?
8. Did function fail before logging due to import error?
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h2 id="21-s3-large-file-processing">21. S3 large file processing</h2>
<p>For large files:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">- Avoid loading entire file into memory if possible.
- Use streaming download/upload.
- Use multipart upload.
- Use ranged GETs if reading only part of object.
- Store intermediate files in /tmp carefully in Lambda.
- For heavy processing, use ECS/Batch/Glue instead of Lambda.
</code></pre>
<h3 id="streaming-s3-object">Streaming S3 object</h3>
<pre><code class="language-python">import boto3
s3 = boto3.client(&quot;s3&quot;)
def read_s3_lines(bucket, key):
 response = s3.get_object(Bucket=bucket, Key=key)
 for line in response[&quot;Body&quot;].iter_lines():

## Page 283

yield line.decode(&quot;utf-8&quot;)
</code></pre>
<h3 id="multipart-upload-mental-model">Multipart upload mental model</h3>
<pre><code class="language-text">1. Initiate multipart upload.
2. Upload parts.
3. Complete multipart upload.
4. Abort incomplete multipart upload on failure.
</code></pre>
<p>Lead answer:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;For large file workflows, I avoid pulling everything into Lambda memory. If the file is too large or 
processing is CPU-heavy, I move the workload to Glue, ECS, or Batch. Lambda is best for orchestration and short 
processing steps.&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2 id="22-s3-security-and-cost-checklist">22. S3 security and cost checklist</h2>
<p>Security:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">- Block public access unless explicitly required.
- Use bucket policies with least privilege.
- Use KMS encryption for sensitive data.
- Avoid exposing raw object keys if not needed.
- Use presigned URLs with short expiry.
- Enable access logs/CloudTrail data events for sensitive buckets.
- Consider Object Lock for compliance.
</code></pre>
<p>Cost:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">- Lifecycle old raw files to cheaper storage.
- Delete temporary/intermediate files.
- Avoid excessive LIST operations.
- Compress large text outputs.
- Use Parquet for analytics data.
- Watch cross-region transfer costs.
</code></pre>
