<h2 id="47-incident-response-framework">47. Incident response framework</h2>
<p>When asked: &quot;Production is down, what do you do?&quot;</p>
<p>Use this answer:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">1. Confirm impact: who is affected, what operation, when started.
2. Stabilize: rollback, reduce traffic, disable risky feature, increase capacity, pause consumers if needed.
3. Observe: metrics, logs, traces, recent deployments, AWS health, dependency health.
4. Isolate: app bug, infra change, data issue, external dependency, capacity limit.
5. Fix: apply minimal safe mitigation first.

## Page 300

6. Verify: metrics return to normal, errors reduce, backlog drains.
7. Follow-up: RCA, tests, alarms, runbook, prevention.
</code></pre>
<p>Lead phrase:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;During incident response, mitigation comes before perfect root cause. After service is stable, I do 
the deeper RCA.&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h1 id="part-v2-k---production-incident-playbooks">PART V2-K - Production Incident Playbooks</h1>
<h2 id="48-playbook-lambda-throttling">48. Playbook: Lambda throttling</h2>
<p>Symptoms:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">- CloudWatch Throttles &gt; 0
- API Gateway 5XX/latency
- SQS backlog increasing
- async events delayed
</code></pre>
<p>Causes:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">- account concurrency limit reached
- reserved concurrency too low
- another function consumed concurrency
- sudden traffic spike
- long duration increases concurrency
</code></pre>
<p>Debug:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">1. Check ConcurrentExecutions and Throttles.
2. Check function reserved concurrency.
3. Check account concurrency usage.
4. Check duration increase.
5. Check downstream slowness.
</code></pre>
<p>Mitigation:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">- increase reserved/account concurrency if safe
- reduce duration by tuning memory/code
- queue non-critical work
- protect downstream with maximum concurrency
- request limit increase if needed
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h2 id="49-playbook-sqs-messages-duplicating">49. Playbook: SQS messages duplicating</h2>
<p>Important truth:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">Duplicate messages are normal in at-least-once systems.
</code></pre>
<p>Causes:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">- visibility timeout too short
- Lambda timeout/failure before delete
- batch failure retries all messages
- network issue during delete
- producer sent duplicate event
</code></pre>
<p>Fix:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">- idempotency key
- partial batch response
- increase visibility timeout
- reduce batch size
- tune Lambda timeout
- dedupe at producer if possible
</code></pre>
<hr />

## Page 301

<h2 id="50-playbook-dlq-suddenly-filling">50. Playbook: DLQ suddenly filling</h2>
<p>Debug:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">1. Sample DLQ messages.
2. Identify common event_type/source.
3. Check Lambda logs around message_id/job_id.
4. Separate transient failures from poison data.
5. Check recent deploy/config/schema changes.
6. Fix root cause.
7. Replay controlled batches.
</code></pre>
<p>Do not:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">- blindly replay all DLQ messages
- delete DLQ without analysis
- increase maxReceiveCount without fixing issue
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h2 id="51-playbook-api-gateway-502">51. Playbook: API Gateway 502</h2>
<p>Likely causes:</p>
