<h1 id="part-v2-n---architecture-case-studies">PART V2-N - Architecture Case Studies</h1>
<h2 id="61-case-study-1-scalable-document-processing-system">61. Case Study 1: Scalable document processing 
system</h2>
<p>Requirement:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">Users upload PDFs. System extracts data, stores structured output, and lets 
user check status.
</code></pre>
<p>Architecture:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">React frontend
 -&gt; API Gateway/FastAPI creates job + presigned upload URL
 -&gt; Browser uploads PDF to S3 raw/
 -&gt; S3 event or API publishes job to SQS
 -&gt; Lambda worker validates file and starts Textract
 -&gt; Textract async result through SNS/SQS
 -&gt; Result processor parses JSON
 -&gt; Store structured data in PostgreSQL/DynamoDB

## Page 306

-&gt; Store raw result in S3 processed/
 -&gt; Frontend polls GET /jobs/{job_id} or receives websocket/SNS push through app layer
</code></pre>
<p>Design details:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">- job_id generated before upload
- idempotency key = job_id + bucket + key + version
- raw/ and processed/ prefixes separated
- status table: UPLOAD_PENDING, QUEUED, PROCESSING, EXTRACTED, FAILED
- DLQ for failed extraction messages
- alarms on queue age, Lambda errors, DLQ depth
- KMS encryption for sensitive invoices
- lifecycle policy for raw/intermediate files
</code></pre>
<p>Possible DB schema:</p>
<pre><code class="language-sql">CREATE TABLE document_jobs (
 job_id UUID PRIMARY KEY,
 user_id UUID NOT NULL,
 bucket TEXT NOT NULL,
 object_key TEXT NOT NULL,
 status TEXT NOT NULL,
 error_message TEXT,
 created_at TIMESTAMP NOT NULL DEFAULT now(),
 updated_at TIMESTAMP NOT NULL DEFAULT now()
);
CREATE TABLE extracted_invoices (
 id UUID PRIMARY KEY,
 job_id UUID REFERENCES document_jobs(job_id),
 invoice_number TEXT,
 invoice_date DATE,
 vendor_name TEXT,
 total_amount NUMERIC(12, 2),
 raw_json_s3_key TEXT
);
</code></pre>
<p>Lead trade-offs:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">- Lambda is good for orchestration; Glue/ECS may be better for heavy PDF/image 
processing.
- SQS decouples upload from extraction and provides retry/DLQ.
- PostgreSQL is good for queryable structured invoice data.
- S3 is the source for raw files and large JSON outputs.
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h2 id="62-case-study-2-webhook-ingestion-at-scale">62. Case Study 2: Webhook ingestion at scale</h2>
<p>Requirement:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">Receive payment/telephony/messaging webhooks reliably.
</code></pre>
<p>Architecture:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">Webhook provider
 -&gt; API Gateway/Lambda or ALB/FastAPI
 -&gt; verify signature
 -&gt; store raw webhook event
 -&gt; enqueue event to SQS/EventBridge
 -&gt; worker processes event idempotently
 -&gt; update DB/business state
</code></pre>
<p>Important:</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">- respond quickly to provider
- never do heavy work synchronously

## Page 307

- verify signature before processing
- dedupe by provider event_id
- store raw payload for audit/debug
- handle out-of-order events
</code></pre>
<p>Example idempotency table:</p>
<pre><code class="language-sql">CREATE TABLE webhook_events (
 provider TEXT NOT NULL,
 event_id TEXT NOT NULL,
 event_type TEXT NOT NULL,
 status TEXT NOT NULL,
 payload JSONB NOT NULL,
 created_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT now(),
 PRIMARY KEY (provider, event_id)
);
</code></pre>
<p>Lead answer:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;For webhooks, I acknowledge fast and process async. I verify signatures, persist the raw event, dedupe 
on provider event ID, and design for retries and out-of-order delivery.&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
