<h2 id="104-presigned-s3-upload-visual-route-map">104. Presigned S3 upload - visual route map</h2>
<p>For large uploads, do not upload the file through API Gateway/Lambda unless the file is small and the 
latency is acceptable. Generate a presigned URL, upload directly to S3, and trigger async processing.</p>
<div class="flow-visual"><div class="flow-node">React client</div><div class="flow-arrow">1. request upload 
URL</div><div class="flow-node">API Lambda</div><div class="flow-arrow">2. presigned URL</div><div class="flow-
node">React client</div><div class="flow-arrow">3. PUT file</div><div class="flow-node">S3 raw bucket</div><div 
class="flow-arrow">4. event</div><div class="flow-node">SQS/Lambda worker</div></div>
<pre><code class="language-python">import boto3
s3 = boto3.client("s3")
def create_upload_url(bucket: str, key: str, content_type: str):
 return s3.generate_presigned_url(
 ClientMethod="put_object",
 Params={
 "Bucket": bucket,
 "Key": key,
 "ContentType": content_type,
 },
 ExpiresIn=900,
 )</code></pre>
<p><strong>Interview answer:</strong> "For large file uploads, I avoid passing the binary through Lambda. I use 
presigned S3 upload, then process asynchronously through S3 event/SQS/Lambda/Step Functions."</p>
